"""
mkt-christ | Leviticus | chapters 5–7
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-leviticus-5-7-fill.py

Ch 5: Graduated chatat (poverty provision points to universal atonement access);
      viduy as 1 John 1:9 type; asham as Isa 53:10 guilt-offering terminology;
      chomesh surcharge and Christ's active-obedience restitution.
Ch 6: Altar fire never quenched as Heb 7:24-25 type; high priest's total self-offering;
      sin-offering blood on garments as 1 John 1:7 type; priest-who-atones has the
      offering — Christ as both priest and sacrifice.
Ch 7: Toda-shelamim as Lord's Supper type (1 Cor 10:16-22); third-day meat corruption
      boundary (Acts 2:27); blood-is-life pointing to 1 Pet 1:18-19; wave offering
      gesture as resurrection type; fat-reserved-for-YHWH and Col 2:9.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DATA = {
  "5": {
    "1": "<p>The obligation to testify publicly when called — the one who hears the public adjuration and withholds testimony bears guilt. Christ perfectly fulfills the opposite: he testifies truthfully before Pilate about his own identity (John 18:37: 'For this I was born and for this I have come into the world — to bear witness to the truth') even knowing the testimony will lead to his death. Where Israel failed to testify, the one faithful Witness (Rev 1:5: <em>ho martus ho pistos</em>) bears witness without flinching.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Inadvertent contact with uncleanness creates guilt even without awareness. Christ enters the full range of human uncleanness not inadvertently but deliberately: he touches the leper (Mark 1:41), the corpse (Luke 7:14), the hemorrhaging woman (Mark 5:27-29) — reversing the transmission direction. Where Levitical contact made the clean unclean, his contact makes the unclean clean. He bears the inadvertent-contamination category by experiencing it in full and overcoming it.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Human uncleanness contracted unknowingly still creates liability. The mechanism of Christ's atonement covers not only known sins but the full range of human guilt, including what was not known to be guilt at the time: 'Father, forgive them, for they know not what they do' (Luke 23:34). The intercessory prayer at the cross addresses precisely this inadvertent category of sin — the crucifiers do not know they are sinning against the Son of God.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The rash oath forgotten — impulsive speech that becomes a forgotten liability. Christ's atonement covers the full range of speech sins, including the careless words that humans dismiss as insignificant: 'I tell you, on the day of judgment people will give account for every careless word they speak' (Matt 12:36). The rash-oath category confirms that the atonement system takes seriously what human consciousness often minimizes.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Confession (<em>viduy</em>) must precede the offering: 'he shall confess the sin he has committed.' The verbal acknowledgment is not merely procedural but constitutive of the atonement transaction. This structure is the type of 1 John 1:9: 'If we confess our sins, he is faithful and just to forgive us our sins and to cleanse us from all unrighteousness.' The pattern is identical: verbal acknowledgment → priestly atonement → forgiveness. Christ's sacrifice provides the permanent atoning mechanism; the confession is the point of application.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The female animal as the base-level sin offering for the graduated scale — accessible to ordinary Israelites. The chatat system's design goal is universal atonement access; no Israelite is too poor for atonement. Christ's atonement is offered without cost to the spiritually poor: 'Come, everyone who thirsts, come to the waters; and he who has no money, come, buy and eat' (Isa 55:1). The graduated chatat's sliding scale is the type of atonement offered equally to rich and poor, 'without money and without price.'</p>",
    "7": "<p>The first tier of poverty provision: two birds when a lamb is unaffordable. The system refuses to price the poor out of atonement. Christ is born into precisely this economic category: Mary's offering at the purification (Luke 2:24: 'a pair of turtledoves or two young pigeons') is the poor person's bird offering of Lev 12:8, confirming that the one who would provide final atonement for all entered the world in the economic position of those for whom the poverty provision was designed.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The bird sin offering — wringing the neck without severing completely. The violence of the sacrifice is inescapable even in the minimal form; the bird must die. Hebrews 9:22: 'without the shedding of blood there is no forgiveness of sins.' The scaled-down offering maintains the irreducible requirement: blood must be shed. The smallest offering and the largest point to the same necessity that Christ's death fulfills.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The blood sprinkled on the altar side, remainder drained at the base. The partial blood manipulation of the bird offering accomplishes the same atoning function as the full blood manipulation of the lamb. The efficacy does not scale with the size of the offering; the blood of any legitimate sacrifice atones because YHWH has given blood for atonement (Lev 17:11). Christ's blood does not atone in proportion to his greatness but because the Father appointed it as the one final atonement.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The second bird as a burnt offering — complete consecration following atonement. The two-bird sequence (chatat + olah) rehearses the pattern that frames Levitical worship: first remove the barrier of sin (chatat), then offer the life fully to God (olah). Christ's death on the cross is both: the sin offering that removes the barrier and the burnt offering of total self-consecration to the Father ('Not my will, but yours be done,' Luke 22:42).</p>",
    "11": "<p>The flour offering for the absolutely poor — no oil, no frankincense, because it is for a sin offering. Even a handful of flour can accomplish atonement when brought with confession and priestly mediation. The minimal offering is still received as the maximum: Christ's single sacrifice receives the poorest confessing sinner exactly as it receives the one who comes with full understanding. Access is not proportional to resources.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The handful (<em>kometz</em>) burned as the memorial portion (<em>azkarah</em>) before YHWH. The handful represents the whole; the remainder becomes priestly food. Christ's single act of self-offering ('once for all,' Heb 7:27) represents and accomplishes atonement for all; the 'remainder' — the ongoing intercessory work — belongs to the eternal High Priest who 'always lives to make intercession' (Heb 7:25).</p>",
    "13": "<p>The identical atonement-forgiveness formula regardless of economic tier: 'the priest shall make atonement for him... and he shall be forgiven.' The flour offering produces the same forensic result as the lamb. The type teaches what the antitype accomplishes: Christ's one sacrifice atones equally for all regardless of the quality or quantity of the worshiper's approach. 'There is neither Jew nor Greek, slave nor free... for you are all one in Christ Jesus' (Gal 3:28).</p>",
    "14": "<p>The revelation formula introducing the guilt offering for sacrilege against holy things. The asham begins with the category of violations against YHWH's own portion. Christ's atonement addresses not only interpersonal sin but the sacrilege against God's holiness itself — the defilement of the sanctuary of creation by human sin that extends from the first Adam's transgression (Rom 5:12-21) to the accumulated desecration of God's world.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The guilt offering for unintentional sacrilege — failing to give YHWH what is rightly his. The asham addresses the chronic human failure to honor YHWH's proprietary claims on time, tithe, firstfruits, and devotion. Christ's active obedience, his perfect lifetime of giving YHWH everything that was due, is the positive fulfillment of the asham's requirement: not only removing the deficit through atonement but restoring what was owed in full through perfect covenant faithfulness.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The chomesh (one-fifth restitution surcharge): making good the violation plus twenty percent. Christ's active obedience exceeds mere substitutionary coverage of the debt; the surplus of his righteousness (<em>perisseuein</em>, the overflow of grace, Rom 5:17: 'those who receive the abundance of grace and the free gift of righteousness will reign in life through the one man Jesus Christ') is the antitype of the chomesh — Christ restores beyond the minimum, generating an overflow of righteousness that is credited to believers.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The asham for uncertain violations — the 'floating guilt' offering brought when one suspects but does not know a violation has occurred. Christ's atonement covers not only known sins but the full range of human failure including what was not perceived as sin. Paul: 'My conscience is clear, but that does not make me innocent' (1 Cor 4:4) — the category of unknown culpability that the precautionary asham addresses is permanently resolved by the comprehensive scope of Christ's sacrifice.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The ram of the guilt offering and the forgiveness formula: 'he shall be forgiven for the mistake that he made unintentionally.' Unintentional sin is no less covered by the asham than deliberate sin; the scope of forgiveness is total. Hebrews 10:10: 'by that will we have been sanctified through the offering of the body of Jesus Christ once for all.' The completeness of Christ's offering covers the full spectrum of human culpability including the inadvertent.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The declarative formula: <em>asham hu</em> (it is a guilt offering) — the offering's identity is declared before it functions. The most important declaration in the NT is the parallel: Isaiah 53:10 uses the same term for the Servant: <em>tasim asham nafesho</em> (when you make his life a guilt offering / when his soul is made an asham). The Servant of YHWH's death is explicitly identified as an asham — not merely any sacrifice but the guilt-offering that covers sacrilege and requires the chomesh restitution. Christ's death is the fulfillment of the entire asham category.</p>"
  },
  "6": {
    "1": "<p>The priestly service rubrics begin; ch 6 addresses what the priests do after the offering is presented. The ongoing priestly ministry — altar tending, fire maintenance, distribution of portions — is the type of Christ's ongoing high-priestly ministry after his one sacrifice: he 'always lives to make intercession' (Heb 7:25), maintaining the eternal covenant through perpetual intercession.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The asham for interpersonal fraud gains its cultic dimension from the false oath in YHWH's name. Christ tells Pilate he speaks truth (John 18:37); he speaks truth before the Sanhedrin that will condemn him (Mark 14:62). The truthfulness of the witness provides the foundation for the atonement that covers oath-breaking; Christ who never swore falsely covers those who have.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The false oath as the hinge that turns interpersonal tort into sacrilege. The profanation of the divine name through false swearing is the deepest category of speech violation. Christ's Name is the one invoked by believers in prayer, baptism, and confession; his perfect truthfulness ensures that the Name invoked is not an empty guarantor but the living reality behind every believing confession.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Restoration of the specific item taken — restitution precedes the sacrifice. The principle that relationship-repair must accompany sacrifice is stated in Christ's teaching: 'Leave your gift there before the altar and go. First be reconciled to your brother, and then come and offer your gift' (Matt 5:23-24). The asham's mandatory restitution-before-sacrifice structure underlies the Lord's teaching on reconciliation as a prerequisite for worship.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The chomesh paid on the day of guilt-realization — same-day restitution, not delayed compliance. The urgency of restitution mirrors Christ's once-for-all atoning act; the cross is not a promissory note but a fully accomplished payment. 'It is finished' (John 19:30: <em>tetelestai</em>, the commercial term for 'paid in full') is the declaration that the restitution has been completed on the day required, without delay.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The ram guilt offering after full restitution — the sacrifice follows the civil restoration, not replacing it. Both are required. Christ's sacrifice provides the cultic atonement dimension; his active obedience provides the civil restitution dimension. The asham structure requires both: the cross removes guilt before God; the overflow of his righteousness restores what was owed to God's justice.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The comprehensive forgiveness formula: 'he shall be forgiven for any of the things that one may do and thereby become guilty.' The breadth of the formula covers every category of interpersonal wrong that has a perjury dimension. Christ's forgiveness is equally comprehensive: 'The blood of Jesus his Son cleanses us from all sin' (1 John 1:7) — not a category list but a universal coverage.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The altar fire that must never go out — the perpetual burnt offering maintained through the night and renewed each morning. The eternal altar fire is the type of Christ's eternal priesthood: 'he holds his priesthood permanently, because he continues forever... he always lives to make intercession' (Heb 7:24-25). The never-quenched fire on the altar of the wilderness sanctuary was the anticipation of the permanently efficacious sacrifice of the one who 'entered once for all into the holy places' (Heb 9:12).</p>",
    "9": "<p>The <em>olah</em> on the hearth all night until morning. The burnt offering placed at evening burns through the darkness of the night. Christ's body lay in the tomb through the darkness of death — the darkness of Gethsemane, the three hours of darkness at Golgotha (Matt 27:45), the sealed tomb — before the morning of resurrection. The altar fire through the night is the type of the divine life that persists through death's darkness.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The priestly linen garments for ash removal — even the mundane task of clearing ashes requires sacred vestments. The priestly ministry has no secular zone; even the removal of the remnants of yesterday's sacrifice is sacred work. Christ's priestly ministry is continuous: the 'ashes' of human failure — the accumulated waste of lives lived apart from God — are tended by the eternal Priest who makes 'all things new' (Rev 21:5).</p>",
    "11": "<p>The change of garments for carrying ashes outside the camp — the two-stage holiness gradient. Christ 'suffered outside the gate in order to sanctify the people through his own blood' (Heb 13:12). The ashes carried outside the camp to the clean place anticipate the sin-laden offering burned outside the camp (Lev 4:12,21; 16:27) and ultimately the crucifixion outside Jerusalem's walls.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The daily wood added to the fire, the arrangement of the burnt offering, the burning of the peace offering fat — the ongoing priestly service as the pattern of Christ's continual intercession. The priest who kept the fire alive maintained the possibility of ongoing atonement; Christ 'always lives to make intercession' (Heb 7:25), maintaining the permanent opening to YHWH that his sacrifice achieved.</p>",
    "13": "<p><em>Esh tamid tuqad al-ha-mizbeach lo tikhbeh</em> — fire shall be kept burning on the altar continually; it shall not go out. The eternal altar fire is the single most direct spatial type in the sanctuary of Christ's eternal priesthood. The fire that Lev 9:24 records as descending from YHWH at the sanctuary's inauguration must never be quenched. The priestly responsibility to maintain it is fulfilled by the one who is 'the same yesterday and today and forever' (Heb 13:8) — his priestly intercession knows no quenching.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The grain offering rubric — priestly handling after presentation. The grain offering is the offering of the fruit of human labor (field, mill, oven) given to YHWH. Christ receives the fruit of his people's lives — their deeds, prayers, service — as the High Priest who presents them before the Father: 'through him let us continually offer up a sacrifice of praise to God' (Heb 13:15). The ongoing grain offering ministry pictures the perpetual mediation of human worship through the priestly Christ.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The handful burned as azkarah before YHWH — the token that represents the whole. The azkarah (memorial/reminder) of the grain offering anticipates the Lord's Supper's 'do this in remembrance (<em>anamnesis</em>) of me' (Luke 22:19; 1 Cor 11:24-25). The Supper is not merely a memorial for the disciples but a presenting of Christ's sacrifice before the Father — an ongoing azkarah that the eternal High Priest makes of his one offering.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The priestly portion of the grain offering eaten unleavened in a holy place. The priests eat the holy bread within the sanctuary courts. Christ feeds his people with himself: 'I am the bread of life' (John 6:35,48,51). The priests' eating of the holy grain offering is the type of the eucharistic feast in which the people of God feed on the bread of Christ's body — the unleavened bread of sincerity and truth (1 Cor 5:8).</p>",
    "17": "<p>Most holy — the grain offering shares the highest sanctity category with chatat and asham. Christ's sacrifice encompasses all three: he is the chatat (sin offering that atones), the asham (guilt offering that restores), and the minchah (grain offering that consecrates the life to God). The three-fold most-holy category is united in one offering: 'For our sake he made him to be sin who knew no sin, so that in him we might become the righteousness of God' (2 Cor 5:21).</p>",
    "18": "<p>Whatever touches the most-holy grain offering shall become holy (<em>kol asher yigga bahem yiqdash</em>). The consecrating touch — contact with the most holy makes holy rather than defiling. This is the reverse of impurity transmission. Christ's touch cleanses and consecrates: touching the leper makes him clean (Mark 1:41-42), touching Jairus's dead daughter raises her (Mark 5:41), the woman touching his garment is healed (Mark 5:27-29). The consecrating principle of the most-holy offering is embodied in every healing touch of the incarnate High Priest.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The ordination grain offering introduced — the minchat chinuch for Aaron and his sons. The ordination of Aaron foreshadows the ordination of the eternal High Priest. While Aaron's ordination involves washing, clothing, and anointing (Lev 8), Christ's priestly ordination involves baptism (the Father's voice: 'This is my beloved Son,' Matt 3:17), transfiguration (the confirmation of glory, Matt 17:5), and resurrection (the definitive appointment: 'declared to be the Son of God in power... by his resurrection from the dead,' Rom 1:4).</p>",
    "20": "<p>The high priest's daily grain offering divided equally between morning and evening. Christ is the morning and evening offering: 'He himself bore our sins in his body on the tree... by his wounds you have been healed' (1 Pet 2:24). The entire day — from the morning of his resurrection ministry to the evening of his intercession — is covered by the continuous priestly grain offering of his life given in service to the Father and intercession for his people.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Prepared on the griddle with oil — the minchah chavitin's preparation. The oil mixed through the grain offering is the type of the Spirit's presence in Christ's priestly ministry: 'God anointed Jesus of Nazareth with the Holy Spirit and with power' (Acts 10:38). The Spirit-soaked offering is the type of the Spirit-anointed Priest whose every action is empowered by the eternal Spirit (Heb 9:14: 'who through the eternal Spirit offered himself without blemish to God').</p>",
    "22": "<p><em>Kalil le-YHWH tiqtar</em> — it shall be wholly burned to YHWH. The high priest's grain offering is entirely consumed on the altar; no portion is retained by the priest for himself. Christ's self-offering is total: 'he offered up himself' (Heb 7:27); 'the Son of Man came not to be served but to serve, and to give his life as a ransom for many' (Mark 10:45). Nothing of the offering is held back; the priestly self-donation is complete.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Every grain offering of a priest shall be wholly burned; it shall not be eaten. The priest cannot eat his own offering: he cannot be simultaneously the mediator of atonement and the recipient of its benefits in the same transaction. Yet Christ resolves this paradox: as both priest and sacrifice, he offers himself fully; and as the risen Lord, he shares the resurrection-life that his death purchased — he does not eat his own sin-offering, but he does feast with his redeemed people at the eschatological table (Rev 19:9; Matt 26:29).</p>",
    "24": "<p>The sin offering rubric — where the burnt offering is killed, the sin offering is killed. The spatial unification of the most-solemn offerings at the same altar location confirms that all sacrifices form a single system converging on a single point: the altar as the place of substitution. The cross is the one altar on which all the types converge — the sin offering, the burnt offering, the guilt offering all find their single fulfillment at Golgotha.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The sin offering is most holy and must be slaughtered in the northern (most holy) altar location. The dignity of the sin offering — carrying the guilt of others — is the highest, not the lowest, category of sacrifice. Christ's cross is not his humiliation alone but his glorification: 'Now is the Son of Man glorified, and God is glorified in him' (John 13:31). The cross is the throne (John 12:32), the altar (Heb 13:10), and the holy place simultaneously.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The priest who offers the sin offering shall eat it — priestly identification with the sin borne. The priest who performs the atonement eats the offering, literally ingesting the sin-laden sacrifice. Christ's 'eating' of our sin is described in 2 Cor 5:21: 'he made him to be sin who knew no sin.' The priestly consumption of the sin offering is a type of Christ's total taking-on of human sin — not merely handling it but bearing it in his own person.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Sin offering blood on a garment must be laundered in the holy place. The blood's holiness-contamination effect on fabric — purifying rather than defiling — points to Rev 7:14: the great multitude 'have washed their robes and made them white in the blood of the Lamb.' The laundering-in-holy-place requirement becomes the laundering-in-Christ's-blood through which the redeemed are clothed in white (Rev 3:5; 7:9).</p>",
    "28": "<p>The earthen vessel used for sin offering meat must be broken; the bronze vessel must be scoured. Earthenware absorbs permanently and cannot be recleaned; it must be destroyed. The principle of permanent absorption — that sin-laden sacrifice leaves an indelible mark on its container — anticipates the truth that Christ permanently bore the mark of his sin-bearing: the risen Christ retains the wounds (John 20:27). The nail-prints and the pierced side are the permanent 'absorption' marks of the sin offering that cannot be effaced even by resurrection.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Every male among the priests may eat the sin offering — most holy access is for the priestly family. In Christ, all believers are made 'a royal priesthood' (1 Pet 2:9) with access to the 'most holy' of Christ's sacrifice: 'we have confidence to enter the holy places by the blood of Jesus' (Heb 10:19). The restriction to male priests in the Levitical type gives way to the universal priestly access of the new covenant community.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The sin offering whose blood was brought inside the tent of meeting is burned up, not eaten. The most intense atonement acts — blood manipulation in the most holy place — require burning outside the camp rather than priestly eating. 'Jesus also suffered outside the gate in order to sanctify the people through his own blood. Therefore let us go to him outside the camp' (Heb 13:11-13). The outside-camp burning of the most-holy sin offering is the direct type of the crucifixion outside Jerusalem.</p>"
  },
  "7": {
    "1": "<p>The guilt offering is most holy. The asham — the offering for sacrilege and restitution — holds the highest sanctity. Isaiah 53:10 declares the Servant's death an <em>asham</em>: 'when you make his life a guilt offering.' Christ's sacrifice is specifically an asham: it not only atones (chatat function) but restores the surplus owed (chomesh function), providing the overflow of righteousness credited to believers (Rom 5:17; 2 Cor 5:21).</p>",
    "2": "<p>The asham's blood is thrown (<em>zeriqah</em>) against the altar sides — the reparation gesture distinguishing the asham from the chatat's horn-application. Christ's blood was shed publicly, visibly, thoroughly: 'whom God put forward as a propitiation by his blood' (Rom 3:25). The public blood-throwing of the asham is the type of the public display of Christ's sacrifice — 'Jesus Christ was publicly portrayed as crucified' (Gal 3:1, <em>proegraphe</em>, openly depicted/posted).</p>",
    "3": "<p>All the fat portions burned — the richness of the sacrificial animal belongs entirely to YHWH. The fat is YHWH's proprietary portion across all sacrifice types. Paul: 'in him all the fullness (<em>pleroma</em>) of deity dwells bodily' (Col 2:9). Christ is the one in whom the divine 'richness' — the full weight of YHWH's glory — dwells; his offering to the Father is not the leanness but the fullness of his divine-human personhood.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The kidneys and liver dedicated to YHWH — the seat of intellect and will given entirely over. Christ's prayer in Gethsemane is the ultimate surrender of the will: 'Not my will, but yours be done' (Luke 22:42). The organs associated with discernment and resolve in Hebrew anthropology are the very capacities Christ surrenders to the Father's will in the garden, fulfilling what every guilt-offering only signified — the complete handing over of the innermost self to God.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The fat portions burned as a food offering — YHWH's portion of the asham. Christ's life offered to the Father is a 'fragrant offering and sacrifice to God' (Eph 5:2: <em>prosphoran kai thusian to theo eis osme euodias</em>). The burning fat's ascending aroma is the type of the sweet-savor offering that Christ's entire life, from incarnation to resurrection, presents to the Father.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Male priests only eat the asham in the sanctuary. The priestly access to the guilt offering's meat is the type of the believer's access to Christ's righteousness: 'Since we have a great high priest who has passed through the heavens, Jesus the Son of God... let us draw near with confidence to the throne of grace' (Heb 4:14,16). The most-holy-space restriction of the type gives way to the boldness of access that the antitype enables.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The guilt offering and the sin offering share the same law; the atoning priest has the offering. The priest who makes atonement personally receives the offering's meat. Christ who made atonement receives the reward of his suffering: 'he shall see his offspring; he shall prolong his days... he shall see the fruit of the travail of his soul and be satisfied' (Isa 53:10-11). The priest's portion is the type of Christ's 'portion' — the people for whom he atoned, now given to him as his own (John 17:24).</p>",
    "8": "<p>The officiating priest keeps the burnt offering's skin — the outer garment of the sacrifice. Christ's seamless robe (John 19:23-24) was not torn but assigned by lot; even the soldiers unconsciously honored the principle that the offering's covering belongs to the one who performs the sacrificial act. The outer garment preserved in the burnt offering type is fulfilled in the seamless robe preserved at the cross.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The officiating priest keeps the grain offerings — prepared offerings (oven, pan, griddle) belong personally to the performing priest. The priest who serves personally at the altar receives the fruits of the offering. Christ's priestly reward is personal: 'the joy set before him' (Heb 12:2) for which he endured the cross, and the people who will forever worship him — his inheritance (Ps 2:8; Heb 2:13: 'Behold, I and the children God has given me').</p>",
    "10": "<p>Raw/dry grain offerings shared equally among all Aaron's sons — the communal distribution. Christ's priestly gifts extend to all his people equally: the Spirit poured out 'on all flesh' (Acts 2:17), distributed 'to each one individually as he wills' (1 Cor 12:11). The equal distribution of certain priestly portions is the type of the Spirit's equal-access gifts given to the entire new-covenant priesthood.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The law of the peace offering — the shelamim, the fellowship/communion offering in which YHWH, priest, and worshiper all receive portions. The peace offering is the most comprehensive type of the Lord's Supper: the shared meal in which God, mediator, and community together feast. Paul: 'The cup of blessing that we bless, is it not a participation (<em>koinonia</em>) in the blood of Christ? The bread that we break, is it not a participation in the body of Christ?' (1 Cor 10:16). The shelamim's three-way shared meal is the type of eucharistic koinonia.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The toda (thanksgiving) peace offering with its elaborate bread accompaniment. The toda is the most festive subcategory, requiring the most bread and eaten on the strictest one-day deadline. The Lord's Supper is specifically a toda in character: 'he took bread, and when he had given thanks (<em>eucharistesas</em>)...' (Luke 22:19; 1 Cor 11:24 — eucharistia = thanksgiving = toda). The entire eucharistic tradition is named after the thanksgiving dimension of the toda-shelamim.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Leavened bread with the toda — the only use of leaven in a sacrificial context. The toda's leavened bread marks it as the most this-worldly, creaturely offering: the product of fermentation, of real time and ordinary kitchen life, is brought into the presence of YHWH alongside the unleavened. The Supper uses ordinary bread and wine — the creaturely, fermented produce of vineyard and grain field — as the vehicle of Christ's body and blood. The toda's leavened bread is the type of the ordinary elements elevated to extraordinary use.</p>",
    "14": "<p>One bread from each type given as terumah to the officiating priest. The priest receives the firstfruit of the toda's bread as his portion. Christ receives the 'firstfruit' of the redeemed community — 'the firstborn among many brothers' (Rom 8:29); the new community born from his todah-sacrifice is his priestly portion, the first of the harvest his resurrection began.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The toda must be eaten on the day of offering — no overnight remainder. The urgent one-day window ensures that the thanksgiving feast is a genuine communal celebration, not a food store. The Lord's Supper is similarly an urgent present reality, not a deposit for future use: 'as often as you eat this bread and drink the cup, you proclaim the Lord's death until he comes' (1 Cor 11:26). The eschatological 'until he comes' creates the Supper's own temporal urgency.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Vow and freewill peace offerings have a two-day window. The less ceremonially charged types (neder and nadavah) permit a more relaxed eating schedule. The variety of peace offering types — toda (most urgent), neder/nadavah (more leisurely) — suggests that the fellowship-meal with YHWH takes varied forms appropriate to the occasion. The Lord's Supper serves both the urgent communal assembly and the more personal devotional settings that the 'breaking of bread from house to house' (Acts 2:46) represents.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Third-day meat must be burned — the third day marks the boundary between valid flesh and corrupted. The 'third day' is the decisive boundary in Levitical sacrifice: what is not consumed by then is tainted. Christ's body does not cross the third-day boundary into corruption: 'You will not abandon my soul to Sheol, or let your holy one see corruption' (Ps 16:10 cited in Acts 2:27,31; 13:34-35). The third-day resurrection is the answer to the third-day corruption deadline — the body of Christ does not become <em>pigul</em>.</p>",
    "18": "<p><em>Pigul yihyeh</em> — it shall be tainted. Third-day meat is void and harmful to eat. The one who eats pigul bears his own iniquity. Paul warns against eating the Lord's Supper 'in an unworthy manner': 'whoever eats the bread or drinks the cup of the Lord in an unworthy manner will be guilty concerning the body and blood of the Lord... eats and drinks judgment on himself' (1 Cor 11:27,29). The pigul warning — eating void/tainted sacrifice incurs personal guilt — is the type of the Supper-worthiness requirement.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Flesh touching any unclean thing must be burned, not eaten; only clean persons may eat the shelamim. The peace offering's cleanliness requirements — protecting the sacred communal meal from contamination — point to Paul's instruction: 'Let a person examine himself, then, and so eat of the bread and drink of the cup' (1 Cor 11:28). Self-examination before communion is the new covenant application of the clean-person-only requirement of the shelamim.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Eating the shelamim while personally impure triggers karet — the most severe penalty. The Lord's Supper eaten in an unworthy manner brings judgment (1 Cor 11:29-30: 'many of you are weak and ill, and some have died'). The severity of the shelamim's impurity-violation penalty is carried forward into the apostolic warning about the Supper's sacred character; both reflect the seriousness of profaning the primary fellowship-meal between YHWH/Christ and his people.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Any impurity source — human, animal, insect — disqualifies from shelamim eating. The comprehensive coverage of all impurity sources matches the comprehensive scope of the self-examination required before communion. The point is not that one must be perfect but that one must have dealt with known sin, sought reconciliation, and come to the table with genuine faith rather than careless familiarity.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The fat prohibition legislation formally introduced. The fat — the richness of the animal — belongs exclusively to YHWH across all sacrifice contexts. The proprietary claim of the Creator on the 'richness' of creation points to the doxological principle: 'to him who is able to do far more abundantly than all that we ask or think, to him be glory... forever' (Eph 3:20-21). The fat that burns on the altar and ascends as aroma to YHWH is the type of all creaturely excellence rendered back to its source.</p>",
    "23": "<p>No fat of ox, sheep, or goat shall be eaten — the restriction to sacrificial species. The proprietary claim applies specifically to animals that participate in the sanctuary system. Everything that belongs to the covenant worship economy ultimately belongs to YHWH. Christ's sacrifice returns to the Father the 'fat' of perfect humanity — the fullness of what human nature was meant to be and offer to God (Heb 10:5-7: 'A body you have prepared for me... I have come to do your will, O God').</p>",
    "24": "<p>Neveilah and terefah fat may be used for other purposes but not eaten. Even the fat of animals outside the sacrificial system is not available for human consumption. The principle of divine priority on the richness of creation is comprehensive even beyond the sanctuary context. Christ's active obedience covers the full scope of human failure to honor this priority: in his life, the fat — the fullness of human flourishing — is offered wholly to the Father without reservation.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Eating the sacrificial animals' fat triggers karet. The severity of the fat-prohibition's penalty confirms that the fat is not merely ritually significant but represents YHWH's proprietary claim on the highest portion of his creatures' lives. To consume it is to steal what belongs to God. Ananias and Sapphira's death (Acts 5:1-11) — keeping back a portion of what was devoted to God — is the new covenant narrative instantiation of this principle.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The blood prohibition extended to all locations, all animals, all people. The universal, comprehensive scope of the blood-prohibition — no exceptions for location, species, or social status — anticipates the universal scope of Christ's atoning blood: 'the blood of Jesus his Son cleanses us from all sin' (1 John 1:7). The blood that belongs to YHWH because it is the nefesh of the animal is the type of Christ's blood, which is the nefesh — the life — of the Son of God given for the life of the world (John 6:51).</p>",
    "27": "<p>Karet for blood consumption. The universal death-penalty for blood-eating confirms that the blood-as-nefesh principle is not decorative but constitutive of the entire atonement system. Christ's blood is the only blood that can be 'consumed' in a legitimate sense — not as food (the prohibition stands) but as the offered life that covers human death: 'unless you eat the flesh of the Son of Man and drink his blood, you have no life in you' (John 6:53). The metaphorical drinking of Christ's blood — receiving his life-given-in-death — is not a violation but the fulfillment of what the blood-prohibition pointed toward.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The wave offering legislation formally introduced. The waving gesture — presenting to YHWH and receiving back — is the physical enactment of the consecration-and-return dynamic at the heart of all sacrificial theology. Christ's offering to the Father and the Father's reception-and-return of him in resurrection is the ultimate tenupha: 'God raised him up, loosing the pangs of death, because it was not possible for him to be held by it' (Acts 2:24). The wave-and-return is the resurrection pattern enacted in priestly miniature.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The offerer personally brings the offerings — the priestly ceremony begins with the offerer's personal presentation. The believer's personal presentation of self to God — 'present your bodies as a living sacrifice, holy and acceptable to God' (Rom 12:1) — is the new covenant fulfillment of the offerer's personal presentation of the peace offering. The shelamim's personal-involvement requirement is transformed into the entire-life offering of the new covenant worshiper.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The offerer's own hands bring the breast and fat as the wave offering. The offerer personally waves the offering before YHWH — the most intimate participation in the sacrificial act available to a non-priest. Christ the offerer and the offering presents himself: 'who through the eternal Spirit offered himself without blemish to God' (Heb 9:14). The agent and the object of the offering are the same person; the wave is self-presentation to the Father.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The fat burns on the altar (YHWH's portion); the breast becomes the shared priestly portion. The three-way division — YHWH (fat), all priests (breast), officiating priest (thigh) — models the structure of the eschatological feast in which God, the mediating Son, and the priestly people all participate. The Lord's Supper anticipates the Marriage Supper of the Lamb (Rev 19:9) in which all three parties — Father, Christ, and redeemed community — will feast together.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The right thigh as contribution (<em>terumah</em>) to the officiating priest — the most honorable portion to the priest who performed the blood manipulation. Christ receives the highest honor from the Father for performing the greatest priestly act: 'God has highly exalted him and bestowed on him the name that is above every name' (Phil 2:9). The right-side priority of the heave thigh is the type of the resurrection-honor: 'he sat down at the right hand of the Majesty on high' (Heb 1:3).</p>",
    "33": "<p>The priest who manipulates the blood receives the right thigh. The blood-manipulation as the critical priestly act that earns the most honorable portion — this links directly to Christ: his blood-shedding is the definitive priestly act (Heb 9:12: 'he entered once for all into the holy places, not by means of the blood of goats and calves but by means of his own blood') that earns the highest honor.</p>",
    "34": "<p>YHWH has taken the breast and thigh from Israel and given them to the priests as a perpetual due. The divine taking-and-giving of the priestly portions is the type of the divine taking-and-giving in Christ's sacrifice: the Father 'gave' his Son (John 3:16), took him through death, and gave him back in resurrection as 'the firstborn from the dead' (Col 1:18; Rev 1:5). The priestly prebend grounded in divine redistribution is the type of the resurrection as divine vindication.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The priestly portions are called <em>mishchat aharon umishchat banav</em> — the portion of Aaron and his sons from the day of their anointing. Christ's priestly portion — the people given to him — is grounded in his anointing: the baptismal voice (Matt 3:17), the Spirit descending (Matt 3:16), the Father's declaration. The priestly portion is anointing-based, not merit-based. Christ receives the nations as his inheritance (Ps 2:8) from the day of his messianic anointing.</p>",
    "36": "<p>The perpetual due throughout generations — <em>chok-olam ledorotam</em>. Christ's priestly portion is eternal: 'They will be his people, and God himself will be with them as their God' (Rev 21:3). The permanent priestly inheritance is the type of the eternal covenant people who will dwell with Christ forever. The Levitical perpetuity formula reaches its ultimate fulfillment in the new creation where the priestly people and the eternal Priest share the divine presence without end.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The closing summary names six sacrifice types: olah, minchah, chatat, asham, millu'im, shelamim. All six are fulfilled in Christ: burnt offering (total self-consecration), grain offering (consecrated human life), sin offering (bearing human sin), guilt offering (restoring what was owed), ordination offering (the once-for-all ordination of the eternal Priest), and peace offering (the fellowship meal restored between God and humanity). The Levitical sacrifice system in its totality is the multi-faceted anticipation of the one sacrifice of Christ whose single act fulfills every type simultaneously.</p>",
    "38": "<p>All six sacrifice rubrics originate at Sinai, commanded on the day Israel was told to bring offerings in the wilderness. The Sinaitic origin formula grounds every sacrifice in the moment of covenant formation. Christ's sacrifice was not an improvised response to human sin but was foreordained before the foundation of the world (1 Pet 1:19-20: 'a lamb without blemish or spot who was foreknown before the foundation of the world') — the eternal purpose behind which the Sinai legislation was a temporal inscription.</p>"
  }
}

